t for local development, these would be found at sibling paths:\n- `../stylo/selectors`\n- `../stylo/style` (for the stylo crate)\n- `../stylo/servo_arc`\n- etc.\n\nServo's test suite (tests/unit/style/lib.rs, line 14) imports the external `selectors` crate, and tests/unit/style/Cargo.toml (line 22) references it via workspace: `selectors = { workspace = true }`\n\n### Rust Compiler's Proc Macro Bridge (No Servo Dependency)\nThe Rust compiler does NOT depend on Servo's selectors crate. Rust has its own independent proc_macro infrastructure:\n\n1. **Main proc_macro library**: library/proc_macro/src/lib.rs (lines 39-41) - Defines the public mod bridge\n2. **Bridge API definition**: library/proc_macro/src/bridge/mod.rs - Defines the server RPC API using the `with_api!` macro that generates type-safe Rust APIs for both client and server\n3. **Bridge server infrastructure**: library/proc_macro/src/bridge/server.rs - Provides ExecutionStrategy trait and server-side implementation\n4. **Compiler's proc_macro server**: compiler/rustc_expand/src/proc_macro_server.rs (line 848) - Implements `impl server::Server for Rustc<'_, '_>` which is the compiler-side server that handles communication with proc macros\n5. **Proc macro expansion**: compiler/rustc_expand/src/proc_macro.rs (lines 17, 33-38) - Uses the bridge to communicate with proc macros\n\nThe communication flow: compiler (rustc) → proc_macro bridge → proc macros → bridge → rustc. This system is completely independent and does not depend on Servo's selectors or style crates."", " }"]}], "userModified": false, "replaceAll": false}

